110
00:11:30.310 --> 00:11:39.090
matheusfranco: But for the ones who don't know spread, but like since then also we got very good updates and new results.

111
00:11:39.250 --> 00:11:45.510
matheusfranco: So spread is a gossip sub extension that replaces the dissemination

112
00:11:46.020 --> 00:11:56.050
matheusfranco: mechanism of gossip subs, and gives you 2 things that people usually treat as opposites which are sender, anonymity, and low latency.

113
00:11:58.570 --> 00:12:11.099
matheusfranco: So just to to to say, this is a joint work from me, from Diogo Cardozo and Rodrigo Rodriguez at the University of Lisbon. and was founded by the Ssv network Dow.

114
00:12:11.560 --> 00:12:18.899
matheusfranco: and we already have everything public. I, if research post the spec Pr. And the implementation Pr. As well.

115
00:12:20.500 --> 00:12:36.489
matheusfranco: So let me set up this stage. First, st gossip protocols give us a handful of properties we care about like performance dissemination needs to be fast, a few seconds budget, and it has to stay reliable and robust as notes churn.

116
00:12:36.560 --> 00:12:47.140
matheusfranco: And the second is anonymity, the long-standing intuition that because a message takes a diffusive multi-hop path.

117
00:12:47.290 --> 00:12:50.560
matheusfranco: The layer would hide it automatically,

118
00:12:50.880 --> 00:12:55.129
matheusfranco: We would hide the one that the peer who originally sent it.

119
00:12:56.540 --> 00:13:03.309
matheusfranco: And the problem is, anonymity is this one property actually, that doesn't come for free at all.

120
00:13:03.540 --> 00:13:13.859
matheusfranco: Even though it is possible to be conquered at some level, and the academic, the academic state of art for it is the Dundelion++ protocol.

121
00:13:14.020 --> 00:13:24.349
matheusfranco: which may or which you all know. It starts with a a random walk, so it forwards the message to a single peer period of time.

122
00:13:24.500 --> 00:13:27.170
matheusfranco: So on number server, whenever it receives it.

123
00:13:27.940 --> 00:13:46.009
matheusfranco: it cannot tell if it is receiving from the choose from from the from the actual source. The peer could just be a relay. Of course, that's the same for gossip, sir. here, by doing a single random walk that you only that has a that you keep a fun out of one.

124
00:13:46.400 --> 00:13:51.670
matheusfranco: You can actually provide this guarantee with proven and everything.

125
00:13:52.760 --> 00:13:58.939
matheusfranco: The the bad part of it is that this costs severely on latency, and

126
00:13:59.200 --> 00:14:07.760
matheusfranco: The community has already looked at it in the past, and it seems that dandelion is infeasible for the consensus layer of activity.

127
00:14:08.350 --> 00:14:22.410
matheusfranco: And here's the uncomfortable part about gossip serves that if you simply changes the if you simply change the fan out from one to 6 or 12, or whatever. then this intuition doesn't doesn't hold anymore.

128
00:14:22.810 --> 00:14:36.049
matheusfranco: And you all have seen these papers, and we have also done it as well, experimentally, with just a handful of passive listeners doing nothing but just taking notes on

129
00:14:36.180 --> 00:14:47.239
matheusfranco: who were the first peers that forwarded a certain message. You can map the validators to their IP addresses very quickly and with very high confidence.

130
00:14:48.120 --> 00:15:05.030
matheusfranco: and that's enough to to target them with a dos attack. We try to force them to miss duties, blocks. incur penalties, and so on, and all of that without needing any type of privileged access, or without attacking the consensus protocol, or even getting to be identified.

131
00:15:05.940 --> 00:15:09.070
matheusfranco: So…

132
00:15:09.620 --> 00:15:16.730
matheusfranco: Also, meanwhile, another issue is that the timing budget for the consensus protocol is also shrinking, as you all know.

133
00:15:16.910 --> 00:15:28.590
matheusfranco: times as lot. Times are expected to be reduced from 12 s to 6, or whatever now or near it. And now, with the ePBS, the individual duties as well, they are

134
00:15:29.380 --> 00:15:32.970
matheusfranco: They they need to be executed also faster.

135
00:15:33.320 --> 00:15:41.310
matheusfranco: So we are heading towards a scenario that needs both stronger anonymity and also better performance, all at the same time.

136
00:15:42.670 --> 00:15:43.760
matheusfranco: So…

137
00:15:43.870 --> 00:15:51.859
matheusfranco: That's exactly our goal. The goal of spread to raise the bar on anonymity while still improving the dissemination speed.

138
00:15:52.610 --> 00:15:53.640
matheusfranco: And.

139
00:15:54.240 --> 00:16:01.469
matheusfranco: to re to emphasize this. And it's not like giving up a little bit of speed to buy some privacy.

140
00:16:01.720 --> 00:16:10.389
matheusfranco: Indeed, the fact is that gossip sub is also not optimized for efficiency today. So this actually gave us a path, a room to to win.

141
00:16:10.520 --> 00:16:15.439
matheusfranco: on both dimensions, both at anonymity and efficiency at the same time.

142
00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:25.480
matheusfranco: So now going to the protocol, how do we do? The key insight is that these two goals…

143
00:16:25.910 --> 00:16:45.749
matheusfranco: of anonymity and and efficiency. They only really fight. If you picture the network as a flat space with every node equally far from from the other, or without you being able to know any information about the peers, and that's already proven in some papers, like the natural trade-off of them.

144
00:16:46.480 --> 00:16:53.660
matheusfranco: But of course this is not the case in in the network. Real nodes pile up in some few dense regions across the globe.

145
00:16:54.380 --> 00:16:59.869
matheusfranco: And that's exactly what we take as as caveat that

146
00:17:00.180 --> 00:17:11.699
matheusfranco: we try to split the problem along the geography of the network. So, following down the line, we keep a probabilistic random walk, but we run it only inside a nearby region.

147
00:17:12.310 --> 00:17:22.069
matheusfranco: where each extra hop that you do hides a little bit more the source. but also costs almost nothing in terms of performance.

148
00:17:22.859 --> 00:17:29.960
matheusfranco: And then you do a worldwide, efficient, smartly chosen hops.

149
00:17:30.130 --> 00:17:32.910
matheusfranco: to carry the message to other regions.

150
00:17:33.850 --> 00:17:42.749
matheusfranco: And, by the way, as soon as I say region, you immediately get the feeling of clusters. And that's exactly what we we build as a primitive of spread.

151
00:17:42.970 --> 00:17:50.939
matheusfranco: So suppose you have peers scattered across the world like through the Us. East, Us. West, Europe, Asia, and so on.

152
00:17:52.480 --> 00:18:05.000
matheusfranco: To figure out what is the cluster for a certain peer, every peer constantly pings each other and a lightweight coordinate system called Vivaldi.

153
00:18:05.110 --> 00:18:11.760
matheusfranco: turns these round Rrts into positions that estimate distance. So you can imagine it like

154
00:18:12.210 --> 00:18:18.910
matheusfranco: your peer stores the list of known peers, and with it it ha! It holds a virtual coordinate.

155
00:18:19.120 --> 00:18:22.740
matheusfranco: such that the heuristics is that the distance

156
00:18:22.900 --> 00:18:29.840
matheusfranco: from you today's video coordinate mimics or is proportional to the RRT.

157
00:18:31.360 --> 00:18:38.159
matheusfranco: and after a few iterations we've already settled on a good position for each peer with diminishing results.

158
00:18:38.940 --> 00:18:46.480
matheusfranco: Then. from the perspective of a single node, what we do to keep all of this decentralized without a central authority.

159
00:18:46.960 --> 00:18:51.590
matheusfranco: We simply take a percentage of all the peers we know.

160
00:18:52.790 --> 00:18:57.600
matheusfranco: We we take the closest ones, and we define this as our interact cluster.

161
00:18:57.700 --> 00:19:06.140
matheusfranco: and everything else is outside is what we call the inter closer, or simply outside, if you if you wish.

162
00:19:07.890 --> 00:19:19.499
matheusfranco: So every node does that independently, and while everyone does this, you will have the picture, even though decentralized, of the regions that you would expect to be built.

163
00:19:20.490 --> 00:19:27.769
matheusfranco: Actually, there is a another split that we do on the outside peers.

164
00:19:28.150 --> 00:19:31.610
matheusfranco: Some peers we call the stepping stones.

165
00:19:31.880 --> 00:19:35.959
matheusfranco: which are the closest outside peers on a given direction.

166
00:19:36.600 --> 00:19:38.650
matheusfranco: and the other peers.

167
00:19:38.770 --> 00:19:49.409
matheusfranco: that are a bit far away. They are called the occluded peers, which means that there is another outside peers that is closer in this direction, and you can simply compute

168
00:19:49.560 --> 00:19:52.940
matheusfranco: the directions by by by computing the

169
00:19:53.380 --> 00:19:57.290
matheusfranco: because sign similarity of the of the vectors.

170
00:19:59.120 --> 00:20:08.609
matheusfranco: And and this is how we try to do a long hop through between regions without having to waste

171
00:20:08.850 --> 00:20:11.499
matheusfranco: Doing the most expensive call.

172
00:20:11.850 --> 00:20:14.650
matheusfranco: and trying to do pop intermediate ones.

173
00:20:15.710 --> 00:20:19.020
matheusfranco: before I show you an example. This is the the whole algorithm.

174
00:20:19.170 --> 00:20:20.680
matheusfranco: on every message.

175
00:20:20.910 --> 00:20:28.009
matheusfranco: Instead of getting the mesh of peers as gossip sub does, we get the entire set of peers.

176
00:20:28.250 --> 00:20:30.790
matheusfranco: and and we run

177
00:20:31.420 --> 00:20:39.490
matheusfranco: 2 2 procedures. One is the intra cluster that decides whether you will keep doing a local

178
00:20:39.670 --> 00:20:51.200
matheusfranco: a sorry, a random walk, or if you, if you branch out, and the second procedure decides, if you will fire the intercommunication system.

179
00:20:51.450 --> 00:21:00.419
matheusfranco: The protocol is parameterized in 4 parameters that controls the fan out and the Bernoulli probabilities for each procedure.

180
00:21:00.850 --> 00:21:05.640
matheusfranco: So as an example, let's say that a node in Europe wants to publish a message.

181
00:21:06.240 --> 00:21:14.399
matheusfranco: at the beginning it falls to just one random neighbor in its cluster. Then this neighbor sends to another one, and so on and so forth.

182
00:21:14.770 --> 00:21:20.730
matheusfranco: And this is all cheap, and because everyone is very close to each other, like few milliseconds away.

183
00:21:21.170 --> 00:21:29.330
matheusfranco: And it is, but it is very important, because that's exactly when you create anonymity for the message.

184
00:21:29.740 --> 00:21:44.159
matheusfranco: and then at some time, instead of just sending to one neighbor, one peer may also fun out, as I said in the end algorithm, and it can do what we call the cobra walk instead of sending to one peer. It sends to this fun out of parameter.

185
00:21:45.350 --> 00:21:47.189
matheusfranco: This is just to speed up.

186
00:21:47.610 --> 00:21:51.559
matheusfranco: the local coverage on on this question.

187
00:21:51.840 --> 00:21:58.199
matheusfranco: Then also, eventually, once the inter cluster Bernoulli coin fires.

188
00:21:58.570 --> 00:22:03.690
matheusfranco: you know, makes a a directed hop to other nearby regions.

189
00:22:05.440 --> 00:22:17.389
